description:
Deeply saddened to learn of the passing of Encik Mahmud Awang on Monday. He was one of Singapore‚Äôs founding leaders.

A widely respected unionist, Encik Mahmud first got involved in union work when he joined the Singapore Traction Company (STC) as a bus conductor. He became close friends with Mr Ahmad Ibrahim, Mr Devan Nair and Mr Lee Kuan Yew, and won the support of many unions.

Encik Mahmud was elected to the Legislative Assembly in the 1963 General Election, and subsequently to the Parliament of newly independent Singapore. In the years when Singapore was in Malaysia, Malay PAP leaders, including Encik Mahmud, Othman Wok, Rahim Ishak, and others, came under enormous pressure by UMNO politicians to choose race over nation. But Encik Mahmud and his comrades held firm in their conviction. Their courage and leadership kept alive the vision of a multiracial Singapore, and enabled it to become the reality today.
 
Mr Lee was forever grateful for Encik Mahmud‚Äôs stout-hearted support at this critical moment in our history, and they kept in touch. At Mr Lee‚Äôs state funeral, Encik Mahmud was one of the pallbearers.
 
Encik Mahmud may have left us, but his legacy will live on. My thoughts are with his family in this time of loss. ‚Äì LHL

(Encik Mahmud Awang (extreme left), a pallbearer at Mr Lee Kuan Yew‚Äôs funeral in 2015. / MCI Photo by LH Goh)

comments: My Deepest Condolences, may God give peace to the soul üò£

comments: The time where our first generation of leaders are slowing leaving us due to old age is inching closer and closer. I really hope that all Singaporeans, young and old, will learn and know how to cherish and appreciate what we have today. Do not lose sight of where and how we came to what we are today.

description:
Great news ‚Äì Singapore Hawker Culture has been inscribed on the @unesco Representative List of Intangible Cultural Heritage of Humanity!
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
Many have worked hard to get our Hawker Culture inscribed on that list. Thank you for your hard work over the years ‚Äì it has been a long but fruitful journey.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
But the biggest thanks must go out to the generations of hawkers for nourishing a nation‚Äôs stomach and spirits. This momentous achievement would not have been possible without their sweat, toil and dedication to their profession. Why not celebrate by ordering your favourite hawker dishes this week? ‚Äì LHL

Great news ‚Äì Singapore Hawker Culture has been inscribed on the @unesco Representative List of Intangible Cultural Heritage of Humanity!
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
Many have worked hard to get our Hawker Culture inscribed on that list. Thank you for your hard work over the years ‚Äì it has been a long but fruitful journey.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
But the biggest thanks must go out to the generations of hawkers for nourishing a nation‚Äôs stomach and spirits. #OurHawkerCulture #ThankYouHawkers

description:
Today is World Kindness Day. If there‚Äôs a silver lining to the pandemic, it is how it has inspired so many of us to step forward to help one other through these tough times. Frontline workers, migrant workers, friends in need, and kindly strangers, through acts of kindness big and small, have shown that the kampung spirit in Singapore is alive and well, even when we‚Äôre socially distanced.‚†Ä
‚†Ä
The National Volunteer & Philanthropy Centre (@cityofgoodsg) will be holding their annual @givingweeksg in December. It will offer many opportunities to help those in need. ‚†Ä
‚†Ä
With Deepavali just around the corner, we can continue to help spread light in our communities. Whether donating to a charity on giving.sg, thanking your food delivery person, or just reaching out to a friend to find out how they‚Äôre doing, let‚Äôs all continue to be kind together, and show that #SGCares. ‚Äì LHL

comments: Hi PM Lee. I chanced upon a post on instagram recently and being a mom, I was deeply affected by it. I humbly seek your kindness to visit @wishforrayyan profile. Rayyan is a 13 months boy who is diagnosed with Spinal Muscular Atrophy. This causes his muscle to degenerate and go weaker and weaker till he dies. Without treatment,  he will not be able to walk, talk or even eat like a normal person for life. Rayyan's mom is a single mother who had also lost a baby daughter almost a decade ago. Rayyan can be cured in USA via Zolgensma which cost 3.1mil SGD. I do not know Rayyan or any of his aquaintance and family members. I am just a mother who hope to pass this message across to whomever i could. Thank you Sir

Today, we held a virtual Public Service Observance Ceremony. In my message, I thanked public officers for their dedication and efforts during this crisis. Many dealt with situations out of their comfort zone ‚Äì serving on the frontlines, in hospitals, migrant workers‚Äô dormitories, and at the border. Others worked long hours from offices and homes, to come up with solutions to the disruptions caused by the pandemic, from schools to businesses, travel and our vulnerable groups.‚†Ä
‚†Ä
There were inevitably shortcomings to our COVID-19 response. We will learn from them, improve our processes and do better. But as we adjusted and strengthened our responses to the pandemic, our officers rose to the occasion, and pulled together as one public service.‚†Ä
‚†Ä
I hope you will join me in saluting our public officers. Without them, we wouldn‚Äôt have got thus far. The fight is not over, the battle is far from won. But together, we will overcome. ‚Äì LHL‚†Ä
 ‚†Ä
(PMO Video by Alex Qiu)‚†Ä
‚†Ä

Met the team from the Assurance, Care and Engagement (ACE) Group today. The ACE Group is a new division in the Ministry of Manpower. It takes over from the Inter-agency Task Force (ITF), which has been doing COVID-19 operations in the migrant worker dormitories since April.‚†Ä
 ‚†Ä
I am grateful to the ACE and ITF teams for their hard work. They have been testing our migrant workers, plus delivering meals, providing medical care, keeping them safe and finally bringing the dorm outbreak well under control. It has been an enormous task, on a scale beyond what most Singaporeans are aware of.‚†Ä
 ‚†Ä
We are now transitioning to a more permanent arrangement with ACE. The migrant workers are returning to work. We have to ensure that they can work safely, live safely, and rest safely, to prevent COVID-19 from coming back. We need support from employers, dorm operators, management, and non-government organisations. We also ask for the understanding of the migrant workers themselves, as we strive to keep them safe and well.‚†Ä
‚†Ä
Thank you all once again for the good work! ‚Äì LHL‚†Ä
‚†Ä
(MCI Photo by Lee Jia Wen)

description:
Met the team from the Assurance, Care and Engagement (ACE) Group today. The ACE Group is a new division in the Ministry of Manpower. It takes over from the Inter-agency Task Force (ITF), which has been doing COVID-19 operations in the migrant worker dormitories since April.‚†Ä
 ‚†Ä
I am grateful to the ACE and ITF teams for their hard work. They have been testing our migrant workers, plus delivering meals, providing medical care, keeping them safe and finally bringing the dorm outbreak well under control. It has been an enormous task, on a scale beyond what most Singaporeans are aware of.‚†Ä
 ‚†Ä
We are now transitioning to a more permanent arrangement with ACE. The migrant workers are returning to work. We have to ensure that they can work safely, live safely, and rest safely, to prevent COVID-19 from coming back. We need support from employers, dorm operators, management, and non-government organisations. We also ask for the understanding of the migrant workers themselves, as we strive to keep them safe and well.‚†Ä
‚†Ä
Thank you all once again for the good work! ‚Äì LHL‚†Ä
‚†Ä
(MCI Photo by Lee Jia Wen)

 ‚†Ä
I am grateful to the ACE and ITF teams for their hard work. They have been testing our migrant workers, plus delivering meals, providing medical care, keeping them safe and finally bringing the dorm outbreak well under control. It has been an enormous task, on a scale beyond what most Singaporeans are aware of.‚†Ä
 ‚†Ä
We are now transitioning to a more permanent arrangement with ACE. The migrant workers are returning to work. We have to ensure that they can work safely, live safely, and rest safely, to prevent COVID-19 from coming back. We need support from employers, dorm operators, management, and non-government organisations. We also ask for the understanding of the migrant workers themselves, as we strive to keep them safe and well.‚†Ä
‚†Ä
Thank you all once again for the good work! ‚Äì LHL‚†Ä
‚†Ä
(MCI Photo by Lee Jia Wen)

Welcomed another foreign visitor to the Istana today. Despite the ongoing pandemic, it‚Äôs a good feeling to return to some semblance of normalcy.
 
Had a fruitful meeting with Communist Party of China Politburo member and Central Commission for Foreign Affairs Office Director Yang Jiechi. As you would expect, we discussed our respective COVID-19 situations. Despite the pandemic, both sides have kept up contacts through phone and video calls. Singapore and China had earlier agreed on a ‚Äúfast lane‚Äù for essential business and official travel between both countries. At the moment this covers six Chinese provinces and municipalities, and hopefully this list will grow if the situation stays under control.

This year marks the 30th anniversary of Singapore-China diplomatic relations. Our ties with China are substantial and multi-faceted. I am confident that by working with each other and with the international community, we can make more progress in the post-COVID world. ‚Äì LHL
 
(MCI Photo by Lee Jia Wen)

Had a fruitful meeting with Communist Party of China Politburo member and Central Commission for Foreign Affairs Office Director Yang Jiechi. As you would expect, we discussed our respective COVID-19 situations. Despite the pandemic, both sides have kept up contacts through phone and video calls. Singapore and China had earlier agreed on a ‚Äúfast lane‚Äù for essential business and official travel between both countries. At the moment this covers six Chinese provinces and municipalities, and hopefully this list will grow if the situation stays under control.

This year marks the 30th anniversary of Singapore-China diplomatic relations. Our ties with China are substantial and multi-faceted. I am confident that by working with each other and with the international community, we can make more progress in the post-COVID world. ‚Äì LHL
 
(MCI Photo by Lee Jia Wen)

comments: Fast lane does not cover majority of Singaporeans doing business in China. Without entry to China, our business is suffering!! We might have to close down. Not everything can be done remote.

It is our govt ethos "never to leave anyone behind." If truly the Opposition wants to be more represented in Parliament,  then be willing to forge together,  leveraging on resources and brains to compete. Else, what I am seeing is a possible 'self-interest' serving by some of the Opposition.  Some are merely treating their stand more as 'debating'  issues from an 'academia' case study.  Without a potential will-commitment truly to work at ground level With the people. So I urge all Singaporeans let no voice divides us into 'polarisation' , never to embrace this downhill stance ofvthe West. But to stay United and Choose Wisely. Give a strong mandate to the new leadership. The journey ahead for the new Team to recover this 20% of Deficit taken out from our Reserves will not be an easy one. To rebuild the war chest for future generations will require 2-3times this deficit. So we must know our Sums right.

description:
This morning, the @papsingapore launched our GE 2020 Manifesto ‚Äî Our Lives, Our Jobs, Our Future.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
This is not a normal election because we are not living in normal times. The central focus of this Manifesto is how we will work together to overcome the crisis of a generation.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
- How to keep Singaporeans and our migrant workers safe and prevent COVID-19 from overwhelming our healthcare system.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
- How to restart and transform the economy, save jobs and businesses, and reskill workers.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
- How to provide one another care and support, so that together we can keep ourselves safe amidst the uncertainties ahead.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
Beyond COVID-19, this Manifesto also sets out the PAP‚Äôs longer-term plans to build a better Singapore, beyond the next 5-year term of government ‚Äî 10, 20 years down the road.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
Singaporeans can rely on the PAP government. What the PAP promises, it delivers.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
We need a strong and capable leadership team, with the full support of all Singaporeans, to put our Manifesto into action. That is the way to secure our lives, our jobs, and the Future of Singapore.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
You can watch my address here on the PAP YouTube channel: www.youtube.com/PeopleActionPartyHQ ‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
‚Äì LHL

- How to keep Singaporeans and our migrant workers safe and prevent COVID-19 from overwhelming our healthcare system.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
- How to restart and transform the economy, save jobs and businesses, and reskill workers.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä

‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä

‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
Singaporeans can rely on the PAP government. What the PAP promises, it delivers.

This is not a normal election because we are not living in normal times. The central focus of this Manifesto is how we will work together to overcome the crisis of a generation.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
- How to keep Singaporeans and our migrant workers safe and prevent COVID-19 from overwhelming our healthcare system.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
- How to restart and transform the economy, save jobs and businesses, and reskill workers.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
- How to provide one another care and support, so that together we can keep ourselves safe amidst the uncertainties ahead.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
Beyond COVID-19, this Manifesto also sets out the PAP‚Äôs longer-term plans to build a better Singapore, beyond the next 5-year term of government ‚Äî 10, 20 years down the road.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
Singaporeans can rely on the PAP government. What the PAP promises, it delivers.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
We need a strong and capable leadership team, with the full support of all Singaporeans, to put our Manifesto into action. That is the way to secure our lives, our jobs, and the Future of Singapore.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
You can watch my address here on the PAP YouTube channel: www.youtube.com/PeopleActionPartyHQ ‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
‚Äì LHL

‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
- How to keep Singaporeans and our migrant workers safe and prevent COVID-19 from overwhelming our healthcare system.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
- How to restart and transform the economy, save jobs and businesses, and reskill workers.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
- How to provide one another care and support, so that together we can keep ourselves safe amidst the uncertainties ahead.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
Beyond COVID-19, this Manifesto also sets out the PAP‚Äôs longer-term plans to build a better Singapore, beyond the next 5-year term of government ‚Äî 10, 20 years down the road.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
Singaporeans can rely on the PAP government. What the PAP promises, it delivers.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
We need a strong and capable leadership team, with the full support of all Singaporeans, to put our Manifesto into action. That is the way to secure our lives, our jobs, and the Future of Singapore.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
You can watch my address here on the PAP YouTube channel: www.youtube.com/PeopleActionPartyHQ ‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
‚Äì LHL

description:
Caught up with the different teams of the Inter-Agency Task Force in an e-meeting today. They have been very busy over the past several months, helping our migrant workers in the dorms during this COVID-19 pandemic.

We discussed their work so far, what comes next, and what we can tweak and improve. We have come a long way, and the migrant workers are now starting to go back to work.

Helping our migrant workers has demanded a multi-faceted approach, with teams from many agencies working together. They have deployed both high tech and the personal touch, and put in enormous efforts to tackle the problem.

It will take us a few more months to resolve the dorms issue. We have kept things under control, and will progressively bring things back up and running again. Thank you all, once again, and keep up the good work! ‚Äì LHL (MCI Photos by Chwee [1] and Lee Jia Wen [2-4])
#SGUnited

comments: Sir, about 3 months ago with limited medical & human resources, aggressive testing was done on the FWs & the dormitories. At that same period of time, arguably there was no aggressive testing done on the other 5M+ Singaporeans, PRs & the other work permit holders. And catchy words like " hidden reservoirs " are coined. Today, 3 months later, some of these 5M+ people will be going to vote in the July election..but under the same risky conditions as before. Because no aggressive testing was planned & done for the 5M+, the asymptomatic & the pre symptomatic carriers walk among us now. The task force should not tell us not to be alarmed to see covid cases rising. Probably its OK to say that 3 months ago but now when Phase 2 is rushed into Phase 1 & then the economy is rushed to open again.. the hidden reservoirs are not flushed out yet & the aggressive testing has just barely begun. After 56 days of circuit breaker days, we are still in the same conditions as we were 3 months ago, still intimidated by the infectious covid bug. Sir, how come there are no virologists or experts on the inter ministries task force briefing & debriefing team. If we are not mistaken, the rep from MOH is a surgeon by training. A Singapore version of Dr Anthony Fauci will be useful to answer many medical & infectious disease questions. Thank you Sir.

We discussed their work so far, what comes next, and what we can tweak and improve. We have come a long way, and the migrant workers are now starting to go back to work.

Helping our migrant workers has demanded a multi-faceted approach, with teams from many agencies working together. They have deployed both high tech and the personal touch, and put in enormous efforts to tackle the problem.

It will take us a few more months to resolve the dorms issue. We have kept things under control, and will progressively bring things back up and running again. Thank you all, once again, and keep up the good work! ‚Äì LHL (MCI Photos by Chwee [1] and Lee Jia Wen [2-4])
#SGUnited

Helping our migrant workers has demanded a multi-faceted approach, with teams from many agencies working together. They have deployed both high tech and the personal touch, and put in enormous efforts to tackle the problem.

It will take us a few more months to resolve the dorms issue. We have kept things under control, and will progressively bring things back up and running again. Thank you all, once again, and keep up the good work! ‚Äì LHL (MCI Photos by Chwee [1] and Lee Jia Wen [2-4])
#SGUnited

comments: Sir, about 3 months ago with limited medical & human resources, aggressive testing was done on the FWs & the dormitories. At that same period of time, arguably there was no aggressive testing done on the other 5M+ Singaporeans, PRs & the other work permit holders. And catchy words like " hidden reservoirs " are coined. Today, 3 months later, some of these 5M+ people will be going to vote in the July election..but under the same risky conditions as before. Because no aggressive testing was planned & done for the 5M+, the asymptomatic & the pre symptomatic carriers walk among us now. The task force should not tell us not to be alarmed to see covid cases rising. Probably its OK to say that 3 months ago but now when Phase 2 is rushed into Phase 1 & then the economy is rushed to open again.. the hidden reservoirs are not flushed out yet & the aggressive testing has just barely begun. After 56 days of circuit breaker days, we are still in the same conditions as we were 3 months ago, still intimidated by the infectious covid bug. Sir, how come there are no virologists or experts on the inter ministries task force briefing & debriefing team. If we are not mistaken, the rep from MOH is a surgeon by training. A Singapore version of Dr Anthony Fauci will be useful to answer many medical & infectious disease questions. Thank you Sir.
description:
Caught up with the different teams of the Inter-Agency Task Force in an e-meeting today. They have been very busy over the past several months, helping our migrant workers in the dorms during this COVID-19 pandemic.

We discussed their work so far, what comes next, and what we can tweak and improve. We have come a long way, and the migrant workers are now starting to go back to work.

Helping our migrant workers has demanded a multi-faceted approach, with teams from many agencies working together. They have deployed both high tech and the personal touch, and put in enormous efforts to tackle the problem.

It will take us a few more months to resolve the dorms issue. We have kept things under control, and will progressively bring things back up and running again. Thank you all, once again, and keep up the good work! ‚Äì LHL (MCI Photos by Chwee [1] and Lee Jia Wen [2-4])

Caught up with the different teams of the Inter-Agency Task Force in an e-meeting today. They have been very busy over the past several months, helping our migrant workers in the dorms during this COVID-19 pandemic.

We discussed their work so far, what comes next, and what we can tweak and improve. We have come a long way, and the migrant workers are now starting to go back to work.

Helping our migrant workers has demanded a multi-faceted approach, with teams from many agencies working together. They have deployed both high tech and the personal touch, and put in enormous efforts to tackle the problem.

It will take us a few more months to resolve the dorms issue. We have kept things under control, and will progressively bring things back up and running again. Thank you all, once again, and keep up the good work! ‚Äì LHL (MCI Photos by Chwee [1] and Lee Jia Wen [2-4])
#SGUnited

We discussed their work so far, what comes next, and what we can tweak and improve. We have come a long way, and the migrant workers are now starting to go back to work.

Helping our migrant workers has demanded a multi-faceted approach, with teams from many agencies working together. They have deployed both high tech and the personal touch, and put in enormous efforts to tackle the problem.

It will take us a few more months to resolve the dorms issue. We have kept things under control, and will progressively bring things back up and running again. Thank you all, once again, and keep up the good work! ‚Äì LHL (MCI Photos by Chwee [1] and Lee Jia Wen [2-4])

comments: Sir, about 3 months ago with limited medical & human resources, aggressive testing was done on the FWs & the dormitories. At that same period of time, arguably there was no aggressive testing done on the other 5M+ Singaporeans, PRs & the other work permit holders. And catchy words like " hidden reservoirs " are coined. Today, 3 months later, some of these 5M+ people will be going to vote in the July election..but under the same risky conditions as before. Because no aggressive testing was planned & done for the 5M+, the asymptomatic & the pre symptomatic carriers walk among us now. The task force should not tell us not to be alarmed to see covid cases rising. Probably its OK to say that 3 months ago but now when Phase 2 is rushed into Phase 1 & then the economy is rushed to open again.. the hidden reservoirs are not flushed out yet & the aggressive testing has just barely begun. After 56 days of circuit breaker days, we are still in the same conditions as we were 3 months ago, still intimidated by the infectious covid bug. Sir, how come there are no virologists or experts on the inter ministries task force briefing & debriefing team. If we are not mistaken, the rep from MOH is a surgeon by training. A Singapore version of Dr Anthony Fauci will be useful to answer many medical & infectious disease questions. Thank you Sir.

comments: Sir, about 3 months ago with limited medical & human resources, aggressive testing was done on the FWs & the dormitories. At that same period of time, arguably there was no aggressive testing done on the other 5M+ Singaporeans, PRs & the other work permit holders. And catchy words like " hidden reservoirs " are coined. Today, 3 months later, some of these 5M+ people will be going to vote in the July election..but under the same risky conditions as before. Because no aggressive testing was planned & done for the 5M+, the asymptomatic & the pre symptomatic carriers walk among us now. The task force should not tell us not to be alarmed to see covid cases rising. Probably its OK to say that 3 months ago but now when Phase 2 is rushed into Phase 1 & then the economy is rushed to open again.. the hidden reservoirs are not flushed out yet & the aggressive testing has just barely begun. After 56 days of circuit breaker days, we are still in the same conditions as we were 3 months ago, still intimidated by the infectious covid bug. Sir, how come there are no virologists or experts on the inter ministries task force briefing & debriefing team. If we are not mistaken, the rep from MOH is a surgeon by training. A Singapore version of Dr Anthony Fauci will be useful to answer many medical & infectious disease questions. Thank you Sir.

We discussed their work so far, what comes next, and what we can tweak and improve. We have come a long way, and the migrant workers are now starting to go back to work.

Helping our migrant workers has demanded a multi-faceted approach, with teams from many agencies working together. They have deployed both high tech and the personal touch, and put in enormous efforts to tackle the problem.

It will take us a few more months to resolve the dorms issue. We have kept things under control, and will progressively bring things back up and running again. Thank you all, once again, and keep up the good work! ‚Äì LHL (MCI Photos by Chwee [1] and Lee Jia Wen [2-4])

description:
Today is Police Day. This year is a special anniversary ‚Äî @singaporepoliceforce is celebrating 200 years since it was formed in 1820.

I was invited to the Police Day Parade that had been planned for today, and was looking forward to meeting our SPF officers and their families there. However, the parade had to be called off because of COVID-19.

Nevertheless, the SPF remains steadfast in their role as our guardians. They have also taken on new duties as part of the Ministerial Task Force on COVID-19, helping to look after our migrant workers.

My deepest appreciation to the men and women of the SPF for their commitment to safeguarding Singapore, without fear or favour, regardless of race, language or religion. ‚Äì LHL

#MayDay is usually a joyous occasion to celebrate the achievements of our workers and unions. But amidst COVID-19, this year‚Äôs event is more sombre.

May Day is an appropriate moment to thank our brothers and sisters, especially those on the front lines, and those performing essential services. You have kept Singapore going, and far exceeded the call of duty.

Our economy has taken a beating from the pandemic. The circuit breaker has been hard for everyone. Businesses and jobs have been disrupted. But we must hunker down, to stop the virus from spreading, so that we can progressively restart our economy.

Meanwhile, the government is working hard to support companies, and protect workers. We are implementing $60 billion in support measures, through the Unity, Resilience, and Solidarity Budgets.

Our forefathers had the foresight to put aside reserves for emergencies like this. We too have to keep an eye on the future, and work together to make sure Singapore emerges stronger from COVID-19.

You can watch my speech on my Facebook Page (www.facebook.com/leehsienloong) or on the PMO YouTube channel (click on the link in my profile). ‚Äì LHL

#SGUnited
#SingaporeTogether
#EveryWorkerMatters (MCI Photo by Fyrol)

comments: Thank You, PM Lee and your Team for all the hard works. At such critical time when many are working round the clock, suffering from loss of income, jobs, loved ones,lack of sleep and countless other challenges, it is unthinkable that people are worried about their bubble teas, their hamburgers, their hair cuts, their lack of freedom, the poor delivery services and a host of complaints. This government has made life too comfortable for too many people.

May Day is an appropriate moment to thank our brothers and sisters, especially those on the front lines, and those performing essential services. You have kept Singapore going, and far exceeded the call of duty.

Our economy has taken a beating from the pandemic. The circuit breaker has been hard for everyone. Businesses and jobs have been disrupted. But we must hunker down, to stop the virus from spreading, so that we can progressively restart our economy.

Meanwhile, the government is working hard to support companies, and protect workers. We are implementing $60 billion in support measures, through the Unity, Resilience, and Solidarity Budgets.

Our forefathers had the foresight to put aside reserves for emergencies like this. We too have to keep an eye on the future, and work together to make sure Singapore emerges stronger from COVID-19.

You can watch my speech on my Facebook Page (www.facebook.com/leehsienloong) or on the PMO YouTube channel (click on the link in my profile). ‚Äì LHL

Our economy has taken a beating from the pandemic. The circuit breaker has been hard for everyone. Businesses and jobs have been disrupted. But we must hunker down, to stop the virus from spreading, so that we can progressively restart our economy.

Meanwhile, the government is working hard to support companies, and protect workers. We are implementing $60 billion in support measures, through the Unity, Resilience, and Solidarity Budgets.

Our forefathers had the foresight to put aside reserves for emergencies like this. We too have to keep an eye on the future, and work together to make sure Singapore emerges stronger from COVID-19.

You can watch my speech on my Facebook Page (www.facebook.com/leehsienloong) or on the PMO YouTube channel (click on the link in my profile). ‚Äì LHL

#SGUnited
#SingaporeTogether
#EveryWorkerMatters (MCI Photo by Fyrol)

comments: Very nice. Your dad would be proud

#MayDay is usually a joyous occasion to celebrate the achievements of our workers and unions. But amidst COVID-19, this year‚Äôs event is more sombre.

May Day is an appropriate moment to thank our brothers and sisters, especially those on the front lines, and those performing essential services. You have kept Singapore going, and far exceeded the call of duty.

Our economy has taken a beating from the pandemic. The circuit breaker has been hard for everyone. Businesses and jobs have been disrupted. But we must hunker down, to stop the virus from spreading, so that we can progressively restart our economy.

Meanwhile, the government is working hard to support companies, and protect workers. We are implementing $60 billion in support measures, through the Unity, Resilience, and Solidarity Budgets.

#MayDay is usually a joyous occasion to celebrate the achievements of our workers and unions. But amidst COVID-19, this year‚Äôs event is more sombre.

May Day is an appropriate moment to thank our brothers and sisters, especially those on the front lines, and those performing essential services. You have kept Singapore going, and far exceeded the call of duty.

Our economy has taken a beating from the pandemic. The circuit breaker has been hard for everyone. Businesses and jobs have been disrupted. But we must hunker down, to stop the virus from spreading, so that we can progressively restart our economy.

Meanwhile, the government is working hard to support companies, and protect workers. We are implementing $60 billion in support measures, through the Unity, Resilience, and Solidarity Budgets.

Our forefathers had the foresight to put aside reserves for emergencies like this. We too have to keep an eye on the future, and work together to make sure Singapore emerges stronger from COVID-19.

You can watch my speech on my Facebook Page (www.facebook.com/leehsienloong) or on the PMO YouTube channel (click on the link in my profile). ‚Äì LHL

Spoke with PM @narendramodi on the phone this evening. We discussed the COVID-19 situations in our two countries. Singapore is in the midst of the circuit breaker. India implemented a nationwide lockdown since late March, not a simple decision in a huge country of 1.3 billion people.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
I thanked PM Modi for India‚Äôs help when we brought home some Singaporeans from India recently. I assured him that we will care for Indian migrant workers here, just as we care for Singaporeans. The migrant workers made personal sacrifices to come to work here. They have made many contributions to Singapore, so we have a responsibility for them.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
Appreciate PM Modi‚Äôs affirmation of our efforts in looking after the migrant workers, and his assurance that they will not forget this.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
India and Singapore are strategic partners with extensive economic ties. We agreed to work together on the challenges posed by the pandemic, keep supply chains intact, and keep essential supplies flowing. ‚Äì LHL
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
(PM Modi‚Äôs official visit to Singapore in June 2018. / MCI Photo by Kenji Soon)

comments: That's so nice.  Feeling so Good to see this post. üáÆüá≥Being an Indian and being in Singapore as a student for the last 3 years.  I appreciate all the timely efforts of Singapore and India.  Big fan of yours. Both Singapore and India have been considerate to curb this epidemic.  Although m little disheartened as these were my last days in Singapore. We International Indian students are concerned with our tenancy and student visa as our exams are postponed due to coronavirus outbreak.  I am also unable to vacate my hostel room as India is in lockdown and no international flights. My hostel contract is expiring in a few days. I am also anxious about the exam. All we can do our least is to stay at home with a calm mind and positivity. This too shall pass.  The rest is beyond our control. I hope the sick all over the world are blessed with good health.

Paid an ‚Äúe-visit‚Äù to the team at the Singapore Ministry of Manpower Services Center at Bendemeer Road and met the Interagency Task Force.

The task force brings together efforts across the Whole-of-Government to look after and treat migrant workers in this COVID-19 outbreak, especially those living in dormitories. Public officers from various agencies have been deployed to the dormitories to care for the workers. Not all speak the native languages of the foreign workers, so we are working with the ambassadors from the Migrant Workers‚Äô Centre who are migrant workers themselves. I was encouraged to learn that the workers recognise our collective efforts and are working with us.

On another front, our Safe Distancing Ambassadors have also been hard at work in the community. Many of us are practising new habits and keeping a safe distance. But quite a few have still not got used to this. Many Ambassadors are volunteers who care, and want to do something. We are grateful for their efforts and service.

I am grateful to the public officers quietly carrying out essential tasks under great pressure, and I am sure you will be too. I am glad private individuals and community groups are also doing their part. They are raising funds for foreign workers, sewing masks, and rendering help to the homeless. May the Singapore spirit shine brightly as we go through this difficult period together. ‚Äì LHL

#SGUnited
#SingaporeTogether ([1] MCI Photo by Zinkie Aw, [2] MCI Photo by Lee Jia Wen)

Paid an ‚Äúe-visit‚Äù to the team at the Singapore Ministry of Manpower Services Center at Bendemeer Road and met the Interagency Task Force.

The task force brings together efforts across the Whole-of-Government to look after and treat migrant workers in this COVID-19 outbreak, especially those living in dormitories. Public officers from various agencies have been deployed to the dormitories to care for the workers. Not all speak the native languages of the foreign workers, so we are working with the ambassadors from the Migrant Workers‚Äô Centre who are migrant workers themselves. I was encouraged to learn that the workers recognise our collective efforts and are working with us.

On another front, our Safe Distancing Ambassadors have also been hard at work in the community. Many of us are practising new habits and keeping a safe distance. But quite a few have still not got used to this. Many Ambassadors are volunteers who care, and want to do something. We are grateful for their efforts and service.

I am grateful to the public officers quietly carrying out essential tasks under great pressure, and I am sure you will be too. I am glad private individuals and community groups are also doing their part. They are raising funds for foreign workers, sewing masks, and rendering help to the homeless. May the Singapore spirit shine brightly as we go through this difficult period together. ‚Äì LHL

Not all speak the native languages of the foreign workers, so we are working with the ambassadors from the Migrant Workers‚Äô Centre who are migrant workers themselves. I was encouraged to learn that the workers recognise our collective efforts and are working with us.

On another front, our Safe Distancing Ambassadors have also been hard at work in the community. Many of us are practising new habits and keeping a safe distance. But quite a few have still not got used to this. Many Ambassadors are volunteers who care, and want to do something. We are grateful for their efforts and service.

I am grateful to the public officers quietly carrying out essential tasks under great pressure, and I am sure you will be too. I am glad private individuals and community groups are also doing their part. They are raising funds for foreign workers, sewing masks, and rendering help to the homeless. May the Singapore spirit shine brightly as we go through this difficult period together. ‚Äì LHL

Not all speak the native languages of the foreign workers, so we are working with the ambassadors from the Migrant Workers‚Äô Centre who are migrant workers themselves. I was encouraged to learn that the workers recognise our collective efforts and are working with us.

On another front, our Safe Distancing Ambassadors have also been hard at work in the community. Many of us are practising new habits and keeping a safe distance. But quite a few have still not got used to this. Many Ambassadors are volunteers who care, and want to do something. We are grateful for their efforts and service.

I am grateful to the public officers quietly carrying out essential tasks under great pressure, and I am sure you will be too. I am glad private individuals and community groups are also doing their part. They are raising funds for foreign workers, sewing masks, and rendering help to the homeless. May the Singapore spirit shine brightly as we go through this difficult period together. ‚Äì LHL

Paid an ‚Äúe-visit‚Äù to the team at the Singapore Ministry of Manpower Services Center at Bendemeer Road and met the Interagency Task Force.

The task force brings together efforts across the Whole-of-Government to look after and treat migrant workers in this COVID-19 outbreak, especially those living in dormitories. Public officers from various agencies have been deployed to the dormitories to care for the workers. Not all speak the native languages of the foreign workers, so we are working with the ambassadors from the Migrant Workers‚Äô Centre who are migrant workers themselves. I was encouraged to learn that the workers recognise our collective efforts and are working with us.

On another front, our Safe Distancing Ambassadors have also been hard at work in the community. Many of us are practising new habits and keeping a safe distance. But quite a few have still not got used to this. Many Ambassadors are volunteers who care, and want to do something. We are grateful for their efforts and service.

I am grateful to the public officers quietly carrying out essential tasks under great pressure, and I am sure you will be too. I am glad private individuals and community groups are also doing their part. They are raising funds for foreign workers, sewing masks, and rendering help to the homeless. May the Singapore spirit shine brightly as we go through this difficult period together. ‚Äì LHL

Paid an ‚Äúe-visit‚Äù to the team at the Singapore Ministry of Manpower Services Center at Bendemeer Road and met the Interagency Task Force.

The task force brings together efforts across the Whole-of-Government to look after and treat migrant workers in this COVID-19 outbreak, especially those living in dormitories. Public officers from various agencies have been deployed to the dormitories to care for the workers. Not all speak the native languages of the foreign workers, so we are working with the ambassadors from the Migrant Workers‚Äô Centre who are migrant workers themselves. I was encouraged to learn that the workers recognise our collective efforts and are working with us.

On another front, our Safe Distancing Ambassadors have also been hard at work in the community. Many of us are practising new habits and keeping a safe distance. But quite a few have still not got used to this. Many Ambassadors are volunteers who care, and want to do something. We are grateful for their efforts and service.

I am grateful to the public officers quietly carrying out essential tasks under great pressure, and I am sure you will be too. I am glad private individuals and community groups are also doing their part. They are raising funds for foreign workers, sewing masks, and rendering help to the homeless. May the Singapore spirit shine brightly as we go through this difficult period together. ‚Äì LHL

description:
Posted a message on our current COVID-19 situation in English, Chinese and Malay on my Facebook Page, Telegram channel, and the PMO YouTube channel. Please share with your families and friends, especially older Singaporeans.

We saw our largest daily number of COVID-19 cases so far yesterday. Many were from foreign worker dormitories. My message explains what we are doing to contain the spread in the dorms, and protect the health and welfare of the foreign workers. We will do our utmost to take care of them.

The number of cases outside the dorms also continues to rise. This is precisely why we needed the circuit breaker. We need everyone to take it very seriously ‚Äî stay home and stop socialising with others. If we do not observe this strictly, all our inconvenience, pain and sacrifice will all be in vain.

In the video I also appeal to older Singaporeans to stay at home, for your own safety.

The next few weeks will be tough. We have to get through them before the sun will shine over us again. Till that day comes, please stay home. ‚Äì LHL

#StayhomeforSG
#SingaporeTogether
#SGUnited (MCI Photo by Lee Jia Wen)

description:
Posted a message on our current COVID-19 situation in English, Chinese and Malay on my Facebook Page, Telegram channel, and the PMO YouTube channel. Please share with your families and friends, especially older Singaporeans.

We saw our largest daily number of COVID-19 cases so far yesterday. Many were from foreign worker dormitories. My message explains what we are doing to contain the spread in the dorms, and protect the health and welfare of the foreign workers. We will do our utmost to take care of them.

The number of cases outside the dorms also continues to rise. This is precisely why we needed the circuit breaker. We need everyone to take it very seriously ‚Äî stay home and stop socialising with others. If we do not observe this strictly, all our inconvenience, pain and sacrifice will all be in vain.

In the video I also appeal to older Singaporeans to stay at home, for your own safety.

The next few weeks will be tough. We have to get through them before the sun will shine over us again. Till that day comes, please stay home. ‚Äì LHL

#StayhomeforSG
#SingaporeTogether
#SGUnited (MCI Photo by Lee Jia Wen)

We saw our largest daily number of COVID-19 cases so far yesterday. Many were from foreign worker dormitories. My message explains what we are doing to contain the spread in the dorms, and protect the health and welfare of the foreign workers. We will do our utmost to take care of them.

The number of cases outside the dorms also continues to rise. This is precisely why we needed the circuit breaker. We need everyone to take it very seriously ‚Äî stay home and stop socialising with others. If we do not observe this strictly, all our inconvenience, pain and sacrifice will all be in vain.

In the video I also appeal to older Singaporeans to stay at home, for your own safety.

The next few weeks will be tough. We have to get through them before the sun will shine over us again. Till that day comes, please stay home. ‚Äì LHL

#StayhomeforSG
#SingaporeTogether
#SGUnited (MCI Photo by Lee Jia Wen)

comments: Dear PM @leehsienloong , thank you to you and your team for all the efforts in managing this pressing matter. I teared at your direct speech to the families of the foreign workers. I hope they are able to see what we are seeing, and have the faith in trusting that Singapore will do our best for their loved ones. Thank you for the meticulous efforts in taking care of the people. Beside those frontline measures that are reported, I appreciate the less mentioned efforts in place to keep the elderly active through e-Getai, exercise shows etc. The government didn‚Äôt have to, but they did. May I also suggest to use mass media to teach the elderly how to set up applications on their mobile phones to facilitate medical teleconsultations where appropriate. Many of them are on long term follow up for a variety of chronic diseases. They are the vulnerable group, yet are also the ones needing to go to hospital outpatient clinics most for routine follow up that may put them at increased risks. Some of them have the gadgets, but do not know how to maximize the use. Lastly, while a lot had been done, there is the group of old folks and/or less fortunate ones who are living alone and may not have access to technology via smart phones or TV. I have no better solutions how to help them at this moment but I know some may have heightened fears due to disempowerment from a lack of information and/or connection to the world beyond their four walls. Meanwhile, please stay safe, get enough rest, as you and your team continue this long, frontline battle against COVID-19. #sgunited #totaldefence

It has been a stressful week not just for the general public, but in particular for healthcare and medical professionals.

We have watched the new coronavirus outbreak in China closely, from the moment the first news came out. Actually we have been preparing for such a situation ever since SARS in 2003. We knew that one day something like that would happen again. So, in a way, this outbreak was a shock, but not a surprise.

9 of the 13 confirmed cases in Singapore are currently being treated at the National Centre for Infectious Diseases (NCID), next to @tantocksenghospital. I visited NCID this morning to see for myself the screening and containment process for affected patients, and to meet and thank some of the people working day and night to treat them. I was very happy with what I saw.

I urge everyone to show understanding and support to our healthcare and medical teams, public officers, the SAF and @pafrenz, who will be distributing masks to Singaporeans over the weekend. We owe them our gratitude for their hard work and dedication.

I have every confidence that if we stay vigilant and united, we can overcome this challenge. ‚Äì LHL (MCI Photos by Betty Chua)

We knew that one day something like that would happen again. So, in a way, this outbreak was a shock, but not a surprise.

9 of the 13 confirmed cases in Singapore are currently being treated at the National Centre for Infectious Diseases (NCID), next to @tantocksenghospital. I visited NCID this morning to see for myself the screening and containment process for affected patients, and to meet and thank some of the people working day and night to treat them. I was very happy with what I saw.

I urge everyone to show understanding and support to our healthcare and medical teams, public officers, the SAF and @pafrenz, who will be distributing masks to Singaporeans over the weekend. We owe them our gratitude for their hard work and dedication.

I have every confidence that if we stay vigilant and united, we can overcome this challenge. ‚Äì LHL (MCI Photos by Betty Chua)

I urge everyone to show understanding and support to our healthcare and medical teams, public officers, the SAF and @pafrenz, who will be distributing masks to Singaporeans over the weekend. We owe them our gratitude for their hard work and dedication.

I have every confidence that if we stay vigilant and united, we can overcome this challenge. ‚Äì LHL (MCI Photos by Betty Chua)

9 of the 13 confirmed cases in Singapore are currently being treated at the National Centre for Infectious Diseases (NCID), next to @tantocksenghospital. I visited NCID this morning to see for myself the screening and containment process for affected patients, and to meet and thank some of the people working day and night to treat them. I was very happy with what I saw.

I urge everyone to show understanding and support to our healthcare and medical teams, public officers, the SAF and @pafrenz, who will be distributing masks to Singaporeans over the weekend. We owe them our gratitude for their hard work and dedication.

I have every confidence that if we stay vigilant and united, we can overcome this challenge. ‚Äì LHL (MCI Photos by Betty Chua)

We knew that one day something like that would happen again. So, in a way, this outbreak was a shock, but not a surprise.

9 of the 13 confirmed cases in Singapore are currently being treated at the National Centre for Infectious Diseases (NCID), next to @tantocksenghospital. I visited NCID this morning to see for myself the screening and containment process for affected patients, and to meet and thank some of the people working day and night to treat them. I was very happy with what I saw.

I urge everyone to show understanding and support to our healthcare and medical teams, public officers, the SAF and @pafrenz, who will be distributing masks to Singaporeans over the weekend. We owe them our gratitude for their hard work and dedication.

I have every confidence that if we stay vigilant and united, we can overcome this challenge. ‚Äì LHL (MCI Photos by Betty Chua)
